03847nam a22005295i 9780822393733DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223937337 a10.1515/97808223937332doi  a(DE-B1597)553318  a(OCoLC)717334929  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aN6537.P5bB69 2011 7aART0160002bisacsh1 aBowles, John P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAdrian Piper :bRace, Gender, and Embodiment /cJohn P. Bowles. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b69 illus., incl. 17 in color  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Adrian Piper's Performance of Race and the Moral Question of Racism -- t1. Contingent and Universal -- t2. Hypothesis -- t3. May 1970 -- t4. Catalysis -- t5. Food for the Spirit -- t6. "Acting Like a Man" -- tConclusion: The Mythic Being and the Aesthetics of Direct Address -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1972 the artist Adrian Piper began periodically dressing as a persona called the Mythic Being, striding the streets of New York in a mustache, Afro wig, and mirrored sunglasses with a cigar in the corner of her mouth. Her Mythic Being performances critically engaged with popular representations of race, gender, sexuality, and class; they challenged viewers to accept personal responsibility for xenophobia and discrimination and the conditions that allowed them to persist. Piper's work confronts viewers and forces them to reconsider assumptions about the social construction of identity. Adrian Piper: Race, Gender, and Embodiment is an in-depth analysis of this pioneering artist's work, illustrated with more than ninety images, including twenty-one in color.Over the course of a decade, John P. Bowles and Piper conversed about her art and its meaning, reception, and relation to her scholarship on Kant's philosophy. Drawing on those conversations, Bowles locates Piper's work at the nexus of Conceptual and feminist art of the late 1960s and 1970s. Piper was the only African American woman associated with the Conceptual artists of the 1960s and one of only a few African Americans to participate in exhibitions of the nascent feminist art movement in the early 1970s. Bowles contends that Piper's work is ultimately about our responsibility for the world in which we live.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aGender identity in art. 0aRace in art. 7aART / Individual Artists / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393733zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393733423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822393733.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles